AGI - Iran's attack against Israel and last night's replica attributed to the Jewish state has renewed attention to their respective air defense capabilities.
This is what aeronautical forces and anti-missile and anti-aircraft systems have both countries, according to the International Institute for Strategic Studies in London (IISS).
<h2>IRAN - Attack
&nbsp;
The Iranian air force counts 37,000 actual, but decades of international sanctions largely cut out the country from the most up-to-date military technology. It has only a few dozen working planes, including Russian jets and old American models purchased before the 1979 Iranian revolution. Tehran has a squadron of nine F-4 and F-5 fighter aircraft, a Russian Sukhoi-24 aircraft squadron and some MiG-29, F7 and F14 aircraft. The Iranians also have kamikaze drones that, according to analysts, does not exceed the few thousand. It also has more than 3,500 ground-to-ground missiles, some of which can carry half-tonne tested. However, the number of carriers able to reach Israel could be lower. Two days ago the commander of the Iranian Air Force, Hamid Vahedi, said that the Sukhoi-24 were in their "best state of preparation" to counter any potential Israeli attack, but the dependence of Iran on these supersonal tactical bombers developed in the 1960s shows the relative weakness of its air force.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>IRAN - Defense </h2>
&nbsp;
For defense, Iran relies on a mix of ground-air missiles and national and Russian air defense systems. Tehran received from Russia in 2016 the S-300 anti-aircraft system, a long-range ground-to-air missile system able to engage multiple targets simultaneously, including aircraft and ballistic missiles. Iran also owns the Bavariar-373 ground-air missile platform of national production, as well as Sayyad and Raad defense systems. "If there was a great conflict between the two countries, Iran would probably focus on occasional successes," said Fabian Hinz, researcher at IISS. "They have no complete air defenses of Israel."
&nbsp;
<h2> ISRAEL - Attack
&nbsp;
Israel has an advanced aeronautics, provided by the United States, with hundreds of F-15, F-16 and F-35 multi-role fighters who played a decisive role in the shooting of about 350 drones, cruise missiles and Iranian ballistic missiles in the attack last weekend. The military air force does not have long-range bombers, although a small fleet of Boeing 707 reconverted to make as flying tanks could allow its fighters to reach Iran by targeted fate. Rainier in drone technology, Israel has Heron pilotless aircraft capable of flying for more than 30 hours, sufficient for long distance operations. The Delilah cruise missiles have an estimated 250-kilometer range, too short to exceed the Persian Gulf, although the air force could bridge the gap by bringing the nearest launcher to the Iranian border. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
It is widespread, but unconfirmed opinion that Israel has developed long-range earth-surface missiles. In 2018, the then Defense Minister Avigdor Lieberman announced that the Israeli army would receive a new missile force even though it is unclear where development is.
&nbsp;
<h2> ISRAEL - Defense </h2>
&nbsp;
A multi-layered air defense system developed with the help of the United States after the 1991 Gulf War provides Israel with several additional options to break down long-range drones and Iranian missiles. The system that reaches the highest altitude is Arrow-3, which intercepts ballistic missiles in space. A previous model, Arrow-2, works at lower odds. The medium-range David's Sling contrasts ballistic missiles and cruise missiles, while the short-range Iron Dome shield faces the type of rockets fired by Hamas from Gaza and Hezbollah from Lebanon - but it can also, in theory, be used against any more powerful missiles missing from Arrow or David's Fionda. Israeli systems are designed to be integrated into the U.S. interceptors in the region for coalition force defenses. "Israeli air defenses worked well during the attack," said Sidharth Kausha, researcher at the Royal United Strategic Institute in London. However, he noted that some of the targets coming, especially drones, were shot down by allied aircraft belonging to the United Kingdom, the United States and Jordan before they reached Israel, "which limited its exposure to certain types of threat." However, he observed, "the sufficient notice given to allow the preparation of a coalition response, means that the system was better prepared than it could have been if exposed to a similar attack with a lower notice", he added.&nbsp;

