&nbsp;
Doha's diplomacy has so far been at the forefront of seeking an understanding that allows the release of the 133 Israeli hostages, since 7 October last prisoners in the Gaza Strip. In this context, Turkey returns to claim with facts a role in the tiring ongoing negotiation. It is on Wednesday news of a forthcoming visit to Turkey of the leader of Hamas Haniyeh, which next Saturday will be received by President Recep Tayyip Erdogan>. At the heart of the meeting there will be access to humanitarian aid for the civilian population of Gaza, but also attempts to reach the ceasefire and avoid an escalation between Israel and Iran. Just yesterday Erdogan had reiterated support for Hamas, called "a liberation movement" and compared to the struggle for independence that Turkey has carried out between 1915 and 1920 against Great Britain and Greece.
&nbsp;
The Turkish government maintains its contacts with Hamas, it hosts the leaders of the movement on its territory and refuses to consider the Palestinian organization a terrorist group, such as the US and European countries. Erdogan, Fidan and the head of secret services also called last week to the leader of Hamas to file condolences after the killing of his three children, affected by an Israeli bombing in Gaza. The Turkish president just yesterday returned to accuse Israel of genocide > and point the finger against "the unconditional support of the West in a massacre destined to remain forever a stain in history".
&nbsp;
"I will fight for the Palestinian cause and I will be the voice of the oppressed population even if I remain the only one," Erdogan said. At the end of last week, first through the US Secretary of State Antony Blinken>, and after the Iranian attack on Israel through the head of the CIA William Burns>, the United States asked Ankara to mediate to avoid escalation. The request followed a phone call between the head of Turkish intelligence with not better specified representatives of Hamas. Erdogan is expected to the White House on 9 May next, where he will meet American President Joe Biden and will once again assert his ability to move on several tables. The conflict between Israel and Hamas has also contributed to bringing Turkey and Iran closer together. The White House focuses on the influence that Erdogan has on Hamas and Tehran, but also on the need of the Turkish leader to try any way to avoid the consequences of an enlargement of the conflict to the whole region.&nbsp;

